VALUES
(40, 28, 12, 44, 4, 5, 22, 'elders', 'Connection of Rulers and Elders', 'Both passages emphasize the role of rulers and elders in the context of significant events. In Matthew, the elders conspire to cover up the resurrection, while in Acts, they confront Peter and John regarding a miracle, showcasing their ongoing authority and opposition to the apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 12, 19, 2, 1, 7, 'had taken counsel', 'Counsel Against the Lord', 'This connection highlights the theme of rulers taking counsel against God''s anointed. Both passages depict a conspiracy among leaders to oppose divine authority, illustrating the futility of such actions against God''s will.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 12, 43, 11, 47, 47, 'assembled with the elders', 'Council of Religious Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of religious leaders to discuss their concerns about Jesus. In Matthew, the elders convene to strategize after the resurrection, while in John, the chief priests and Pharisees gather to address Jesus'' miracles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 12, 43, 12, 10, 11, NULL, 'Conspiracy Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the plotting of the chief priests against figures associated with Jesus. In Matthew, the elders conspire to cover up the resurrection, while in John, they plot against Lazarus due to his influence on belief in Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 12, 44, 5, 33, 34, NULL, 'Counsel and Conspiracy Motifs', 'This connection highlights the theme of counsel among leaders in both passages. In Matthew, the elders take counsel to deceive, while in Acts, the council considers slaying the apostles, showing a parallel in their deliberative actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 13, 40, 26, 64, 64, NULL, 'Resurrection and Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' authority over death and His eventual return. The claim of the disciples stealing His body in Matthew 28:13 contrasts with Jesus'' assertion of His divine power in Matthew 26:64.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 14, 40, 27, 2, 2, 'the governor', 'Connection Between Pilate and Persuasion', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Pontius Pilate as the governor involved in the events surrounding Jesus'' trial. The mention of persuading the governor in the source verse relates directly to Pilate''s authority in the target passage.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 14, 44, 12, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Authority and Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of authority figures acting on information. In Matthew, the plan to persuade the governor reflects manipulation of power, while in Acts, Herod''s examination and punishment of the keepers shows the severe outcomes of failing to meet authority''s expectations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 15, 40, 27, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Blood and Money', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''unto this day,'' linking the ongoing significance of the events described. The mention of the ''field of blood'' in Matthew 27:8 connects to the actions taken with money in Matthew 28:15.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 15, 54, 6, 10, 10, 'money', 'Connection of Money and Evil', 'This connection highlights the negative consequences of money. In Matthew, the act of taking money leads to deceit, while 1 Timothy warns that the love of money results in many sorrows.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 15, 40, 26, 15, 15, NULL, 'Connection of Betrayal and Payment', 'Both passages emphasize the act of betrayal for monetary gain. In Matthew 26:15, Judas Iscariot covenants for thirty pieces of silver, while Matthew 28:15 refers to the payment made to spread falsehoods about Jesus'' resurrection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 16, 40, 26, 32, 32, 'into Galilee', 'Connection Between Galilee References', 'Both passages emphasize Galilee as a significant location for the disciples. In Matthew 26:32, Jesus foretells his resurrection and return to Galilee, which is fulfilled in Matthew 28:16 when the disciples go there as instructed.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 16, 40, 28, 10, 10, NULL, 'Disciples'' Journey to Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples going into Galilee to meet Jesus. The instruction to go to Galilee in Matthew 28:10 directly leads to the disciples'' action in Matthew 28:16.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 16, 41, 16, 14, 14, 'the eleven disciples', 'Disciples'' Encounter with Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of the eleven disciples after Jesus'' resurrection. Matthew mentions their meeting in Galilee, while Mark describes Jesus appearing to them and addressing their unbelief.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 16, 44, 1, 13, 26, 'the eleven disciples went away into Galilee', 'Disciples'' Gathering After Jesus'' Departure', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of the disciples following Jesus'' instructions. In Matthew, they go to Galilee, while in Acts, they assemble in an upper room to pray and select a new apostle.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 16, 43, 6, 70, 70, 'the eleven disciples', 'Discipleship and Betrayal', 'This connection highlights the theme of the disciples'' journey and the presence of betrayal among them. In Matthew, the eleven disciples are gathered as appointed by Jesus, while in John, the mention of the chosen twelve includes the acknowledgment of betrayal by one. Both passages emphasize the significance of the disciples'' roles and the complexities within their group.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 16, 46, 15, 15, 15, 'the eleven disciples went away into Galilee', 'Resurrection and Witness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of testimony regarding the resurrection of Christ. In Matthew, the disciples are called to a specific location, which emphasizes their role as witnesses, while in 1 Corinthians, the apostles'' testimony about the resurrection is questioned, linking their witness to the truth of the resurrection.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 17, 19, 2, 12, 12, 'worshipped him', 'Worship and Trust in the Son', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of worship and trust in the Son. In Matthew, some worship him while others doubt, paralleling the call in Psalms to trust in the Son to avoid his wrath.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 17, 19, 45, 11, 11, NULL, 'Worship of the King', 'Both passages emphasize the act of worship towards a king figure. In Matthew, some worship Jesus, while Psalms speaks of worshiping the king as the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 17, 40, 16, 28, 28, 'some doubted', 'Worship and Doubt in Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of witnesses to significant events involving the Son of man. In Matthew 28:17, some worship while others doubt, paralleling the anticipation of seeing the Son of man in Matthew 16:28.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 17, 40, 28, 9, 9, 'worshipped him', 'Worship and Doubt in Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of worship towards Jesus following his resurrection. In Matthew 28:9, the women worship him, while in Matthew 28:17, some worship him but also express doubt.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 17, 43, 5, 23, 23, 'worshipped him', 'Worship and Honor of the Son', 'This connection highlights the theme of honoring Jesus as divine. Both passages emphasize the importance of worship and honor given to the Son, linking the act of worship in Matthew to the honor described in John.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 17, 46, 15, 6, 6, 'but some doubted', 'Worship and Doubt in Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the theme of doubt among witnesses of the resurrected Christ. Both passages acknowledge the presence of doubt, with some worshipping and others questioning.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 18, 43, 3, 35, 35, 'all power is given unto me', 'Authority of the Son', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority given to Jesus. Both passages emphasize that all power and all things are entrusted to Him.', 'theme', 0.944, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 18, 60, 3, 22, 22, 'All power is given unto me', 'Authority and Power of Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s authority. Both passages emphasize that all powers are made subject to Him, reflecting His dominion in heaven and earth.', 'theme', 0.7899999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 18, 40, 11, 27, 27, 'All power is given unto me', 'Authority of the Son', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Jesus. In Matthew 28:18, Jesus declares, ''All power is given unto me,'' while in Matthew 11:27, he states that ''All things are delivered unto me of my Father.'' This connection highlights the divine authority and revelation of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.692, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 18, 49, 1, 20, 22, 'All power is given unto me', 'Authority of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Jesus. Matthew highlights that all power is given to Him, while Ephesians describes Him as being set far above all powers and dominions.', 'theme', 0.643, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 18, 58, 2, 8, 8, 'All power is given unto me', 'Authority and Subjection', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority given to Jesus, as seen in both passages. Matthew 28:18 states that ''All power is given unto me,'' while Hebrews 2:8 discusses the subjection of all things under his feet.', 'theme', 0.622, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 18, 27, 7, 13, 14, 'All power is given unto me', 'Authority and Dominion Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the granting of power and dominion. Matthew 28:18 states that Jesus has all power, while Daniel 7:14 describes the Son of man receiving dominion and a kingdom.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 28, 18, 46, 15, 27, 27, 'All power is given unto me', 'Authority of Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s authority. Matthew 28:18 states that all power is given to Jesus, while 1 Corinthians 15:27 emphasizes that all things are put under his feet, reinforcing his supreme authority over creation.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
